                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d249">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 839.51/1232.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Minister <persName type="from">Sullivan</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegrams.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Santo Domingo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-02-18T15:00:00-04:40">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 18, 1914, 3 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Minister for Foreign Affairs Grullon, despite all I can say, refuses to continue
                    in the Cabinet unless the consular and diplomatic corps are paid at once. These
                    men are in distress in foreign countries. Thirty-five thousand dollars is
                    involved and the Minister insists he can not continue suffering pleadings for
                    assistance from the corps any longer. I have asked him to defer resigning for
                    forty-eight hours. Please instruct within that time if he can negotiate short
                    loan. Grullon has been very useful in putting through our policy.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Sullivan</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
